passages.text: Table 1.
Association of the SNP rs975739 downstream of the EDNRB gene with non-red hair colors<sup>a</sup>

<sup>a</sup>Non-red hair colors were coded as: 1, blond; 2, light brown; 3, dark brown; 4, black; beta > 0 means association with darker hair color.<sup>b</sup>Adjusted for the top four principal components of genetic variance in the discovery sets and adjusted for gender in the skin cancer replication set.<sup>c</sup>Postmenopausal invasive breast cancer case–control study nested within the NHS.<sup>d</sup>Type 2 diabetes case–control study nested within the NHS.<sup>e</sup>Type 2 diabetes case–control study nested within the HPFS.<sup>f</sup>Coronary heart disease case–control study nested within the NHS.<sup>g</sup>Coronary heart disease case–control study nested within the HPFS.<sup>h</sup>Skin cancer case–control study nested within the NHS and HPFS.<sup>i</sup>Renal function study nested within the NHS.

passages.text: Table 2.
Association of the SNP rs12421680 in the NTM gene with the number of sunburns<sup>a</sup>

<sup>a</sup>The number of sunburns was coded as a continuous variable; beta > 0 means association with increased number of sunburns.<sup>b</sup>Postmenopausal invasive breast cancer case–control study nested within the NHS.<sup>c</sup>Type 2 diabetes case–control study nested within the NHS.<sup>d</sup>Type 2 diabetes case–control study nested within the HPFS.<sup>e</sup>Coronary heart disease case–control study nested within the NHS.<sup>f</sup>Coronary heart disease case–control study nested within the HPFS.<sup>g</sup>Skin cancer case–control study nested within the NHS and HPFS.<sup>h</sup>Renal function study nested within the NHS.<sup>i</sup>Adjusted for age and the top four principal components of genetic variance in the discovery sets and adjusted for age and gender in the skin cancer replication set.

passages.text: Table 3.
Association of the SNP rs3002288 in the VASH2 gene with brown eye color and the SNP rs12520016 upstream of POLS gene with intermediate eye color<sup>a</sup>

<sup>a</sup>Eye colors were coded as co-dominant outcomes (brown versus non-brown eye color and green versus non-green eye color).<sup>b</sup>Type 2 diabetes case–control study nested within the HPFS.<sup>c</sup>Coronary heart disease case–control study nested within the HPFS.<sup>d</sup>Kidney stone case–control study nested within the HPFS.<sup>e</sup>Prostate cancer case–control study nested within the HPFS.<sup>f</sup>Adjusted for the top four principal components of genetic variance in the discovery sets.

passages.text: Table 4.
Interaction between the SNPs rs7173419 and rs12913832 on brown eye color<sup>a</sup> and melanoma risk

<sup>a</sup>Eye colors were coded as brown versus non-brown eye color.<sup>b</sup>rs12913832 was coded in an additive model, with G as wild-type allele and A as variant allele.<sup>c</sup>Adjusted for the top four principal components.<sup>d</sup>Adjusted for age, gender and the top two principal components.

<sup>a</sup>The number of NMSCs was coded as: 1-0, 2-1, 3-2-4, 4-5+; beta > 0 means association with increased number of NMSCs.<sup>b</sup>Postmenopausal invasive breast cancer case–control study nested within the NHS.<sup>c</sup>Type 2 diabetes case–control study nested within the NHS.<sup>d</sup>Type 2 diabetes case–control study nested within the HPFS.<sup>e</sup>Coronary heart disease case–control study nested within the NHS.<sup>f</sup>Coronary heart disease case–control study nested within the HPFS.<sup>g</sup>Skin cancer case–control study nested within the NHS and HPFS.<sup>h</sup>Adjusted for the top four principal components of genetic variance in the discovery sets and adjusted for gender in the skin cancer replication set.
